StickyListHeadersListView now has its own styleable attribute.

This allows users of this library to do things like:

values/themes.xml:

    <item name="stickyListHeadersListViewStyle">@style/Widget.MyApp.SomeStyle</item>
  </style>
</resources>

ListView choice mode support

title: ListView choice mode support
message:
ListView choice mode support

Choice mode support changes according to @JakeWharton comments.

title: ListView choice mode support
message:
ListView choice mode support

To support AbsListView#CHOICE_MODE_SINGLE,
AbsListView#CHOICE_MODE_MULTIPLE or
AbsListView#CHOICE_MODE_MULTIPLE_MODAL convertView returned by Adapter's
getView() method must implement android.widget.Checkable interface.
Since SticklyListHeadersListView wraps all views of the original adapter
to WrapperView ListView can't notify checkable view from the original
adapter unless the wrapper will implement Checkable interface.

I suggest the following simple implementation of checkable support by
the WrapperView. I know that instanceof is pretty heavy operation, but
setChecked(boolean) called only when user clicks on the list item so maybe
you'll consider it acceptable for the first time.

title: Merge pull request #39 from JakeWharton/implementation-details
message:
Merge pull request #39 from JakeWharton/implementation-details

Abstract implementation details inside a wrapper adapter.

title: Abstract implementation details inside a wrapper adapter.
message:
Abstract implementation details inside a wrapper adapter.

Previously, the `StickyListHeadersListView` made the assumption that all children
would be `WrapperView`s. While this would hold true in practice, theoretically you
were not forced to use one of the supplied base adapters and thus could get runtime
`ClassCastException`s.

This change now hides all implementation details of how the list view actually
operates by wrapping the supplied adapter in one which does the work of creating
`WrapperView` instances behind-the-scenes. Because of this, any adapter implementing
`StickyListHeadersAdapter` can now be used.

As an added benifit we also trim down `StickyListHeadersAdapter`'s API.

title: Merge pull request #32 from JakeWharton/perf
message:
Merge pull request #32 from JakeWharton/perf

Performance and style improvements.

title: Performance and style improvements.
message:
Performance and style improvements.

* Use all lowercase package name as per Java specifications.
* Avoid redundant calls to methods (especially with casts).
* Avoid using IDs to look up views. Make `WrapperView` a bit smarter instead.
* Avoid using view tag to keep track of whether or not an item has a header. Make `WrapperView` a bit smarter instead.
* Cache loop conditional when it called somewhere else (e.g., `getChildCount()`).
* Force `StickyListHeadersAdapter` to be an extension of `ListAdapter`.
* Mark three-arg `getView` method as `final` so there is no way it can be accidentally overriden.
